user.biography:
🥃 Whiskey and🍷wine enthusiast.
🇺🇸 Proud retired SOF Army Veteran.  Mogadishu ‘93
🙏 Honored to have walked among so many giants!

node.title: Run to Remember MSG Gary Gordon, Medal of Honor recipient and mate.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Brad Halling on July 17, 2021. May be an image of 1 person.

node.text:
Back to Berlin with the highly classified clandestine unit PSSE. See video in bio.

Working a stay behind mission as well as having a CT responsibility meant that the unit had a variety of tools to work with. Most of the weapons we used were indigenous to the theater. Meaning, we used H&k, Walther, and a few other European manufacturers.

Pictured here is my friend and team mate Rick Turcotte shooting one of the 9mm 
suppressed pistols. Many from the SF community are familiar with the Turcotte name, as Gil Turcotte, Rick’s uncle was legendary and inducted into the Special Forces Hall of Fame in 2018(another post later). Like his uncle, Rick was amazingly skilled, athletic, a phenomenal shooter, and awesome team mate!
Today he is still very involved in the SF community as an active member of Chapter 6 of the Special Forces Association.

I am proud to share these pictures of my friend Rick and feel blessed to have served along side of him and the so many like him! 

Last picture is Rick’s Harley sitting at one of the city’s check points.

Gratitude 

As we continue to push towards an amazing destination distillery we are lining up some of the best bourbon we can find. We will present these amazing whiskeys as our select while we lay down our estate in the new distillery.

All of this is made possible because our fellow veterans and friends @bardstownbourbancompany_ceo (Mark Erwin) and @johnny.whiskey (COO John Hargrove) These men have graciously decided to work with our start up as our Distillery Advisory Partner. We are thankful for their friendship and commitment to our new cause. This is possible because of our veteran connection … veterans looking after veterans!

Additionally, we are grateful for the time and expertise @dannybardstown shared with us as we tasted thru barrels to make our selections!
Thankful and blessed …. node.text:
Run because I can. Many of you know I run on my birthday. Each year I add a tenth of a mile to match my age. It ensures I am and working to get better and go further vs declining. 

I don’t run because I love it, I run because I was blessed to have survived a combat injury and get the opportunity that many did not. I will continue to run as long as I can remembering all ours that have not 
survived or no longer can run.

Looking forward to 60 and 6 miles!😉🏃‍♂️

node.text: Berlin, Cold War continued: Fieldcraft - Developing 35mm film.  We were at an amazing 160th Special Operations wedding last weekend and a friend and Instagram follower asked “how is it that you have so many pictures of your career“? A fair question. Growing up in Special Forces and especially as I became a senior NCO, photography became more and more important. In fact,  it was part of the Operations and Intelligence (O&I) course required by senior SF guys to take in on order to progress in position and rank on a team. It was even more important in Berlin. We had to have the ability to collect intelligence and develop photos to pass in the field environment. Sometimes this meant developing 35 millimeter film in a blacked bag with out seeing it, or in the bathroom of a hotel room. Either way, we generally worked with black and white as it was much easier. We would practice often on each other to develop the skill .... thus so many pictures, often, in black and white! Today it is no longer taught due to digital photography... 🥃🇺🇸🇩🇪 @hallingwhiskey #hallingwhiskey #militaryhistory #berlinwall #eastberlin #specialforcesgroup #specialforces #specialoperations #specialoperationsforces #usasoc #socom #jsoc #fayettevillenc #southernpinesnc #pinehurst #photography #blackandwhitephotography #worldstopwhiskeytaster

node.text:
More Cold War: Berlin. If you have not seen the video about this once Black unit, pls check it out in my bio. 

As a Special Forces Engineer, like on any ODA, I and the other engineers where responsible for teaching Demolitions training. Our stay behind mission would involve direct action missions as well as disrupting lines of communications. This could mean anything from an ambush to destroying railway, bridges, fuel depots or other targets of opportunity. While it was difficult to train in demolitions in Berlin we made it a point to keep all the teams proficient in the basic tasks. Pictured 2nd is us placing charges on a steel I beam. Truly an amazing time. I was blessed with the opportunity of not only this secretive mission but also to work with so many great Americans!

@hallingwhiskey

node.text:
Cold War: Berlin. If you have not seen the video about this once Black unit, pls check it out in my bio. 

1st pic The Dive Team

Being on a Special Forces dive team was very rewarding but had its challenges in Berlin. We couldn’t openly dive as a detachment yet we were still required to maintain proficiency to satisfy the requirements to receive the $175 monthly dive pay.

We had a few options to accomplish this. We could work in small groups doing sport dives, travel outside Berlin to dive, or conduct midnight dives in a location not visible to general public.

One of our solutions was the indoor pool in the American sector. We needed to accomplish a subsurface dive for 30 minutes. This, while not a fun dive, satisfied the requirements. The Command got their pool cleaned without interruption and we got our dive pay!

In the event we had a dive injury, in the basement of our building outside of anyone’s view we had a single man decompression chamber. This, though undesired, could also be used to satisfy a dive if one was willing to sit in there for half an hour!

node.text:
Cold War: Berlin. If you have not seen the video about this once Black unit, pls check it out in my bio. 

It was 1988, only two years before the wall would fall. In addition to our clandestine operations for our stay behind mission, we also had a counter terrorism mission. Being in Berlin allowed for our unit to serve as an emergency assault force across Europe. It was a different time, a time when training activities required for the CT mission would have to be conducted without the knowledge of the Germans or other occupying forces.
As a Special Forces engineer, I was one of the Team breachers. Often, we would go out and purchase European doors to experiment with our explosive charges to ensure we could efficiently penetrate the materials for successful entry. Today this technique has much improved as those moving through a breach typically are not trying to thread their way through a hole!

As I look back today, I am reminded of my good fortune. I saw first hand the behind the scenes of the Cold War and I worked with some amazing men, both brothers and mentors! #gratitude

🥃 to all (of your) wives and Mothers. Happy Mother’s Day!
